---
import TopicLayout from '../../layouts/TopicLayout.astro';

const title = 'Open clusters and moving groups';
const summary = 'Some stars share common origins and motions, allowing Gaia to reveal loose families and dissolved clusters across the sky.';
const nextTopics = [
	{ slug: 'how-stars-move-through-the-galaxy', title: 'How stars move through the Galaxy' },
	{ slug: 'milky-way-as-a-system', title: 'The Milky Way as a system' }
];
---

<TopicLayout
	title={title}
	summary={summary}
	topicNumber={14}
	nextTopics={nextTopics}
	viewer={{ variant: 'neighbourhood', topic: 'open-clusters-and-moving-groups', showHr: true }}
>
	<p>
		Stars are rarely born alone. They usually form in large clouds of gas and dust
		that collapse and fragment into dozens, hundreds, or even thousands of
		individual stars. These newborn stars are initially held together by gravity
		in "open clusters."
	</p>
	<p>
		Over time, these clusters slowly dissolve as the stars drift away from each other.
		However, they still share a common origin, a common chemical composition,
		and a common motion through the galaxy. These loose collections are called
		"moving groups."
	</p>
	<p>
		By measuring the precise positions and velocities of stars, Gaia has revealed
		many hidden families of stars that were previously thought to be unrelated.
		Finding these groups helps astronomers piece together the history of star
		formation in the Milky Way and the movements of our galaxy's disc.
	</p>

	<div class="callout panel">
		<p class="panel__eyebrow">Stellar Genealogy</p>
		<h3>Tracing the Past</h3>
		<p>
			In the solar neighbourhood, Gaia has identified several moving groups that
			originated from the same star-forming region millions of years ago. These
			stars are now spread across the sky, yet their shared motion remains a
			clue to their common birth.
		</p>
	</div>
</TopicLayout>
